ce:section.ce:para:
The data show that C-Dots also have interesting effects on other microorganisms and fungi that were monitored during refrigerated storage. In fact, fiordilatte with active coating and active brine showed a progressive rise in yeast population (Table 2
                        ), which was lower than that achieved in the two coated and uncoated control groups. In terms of total mesophilic counts (Table 3
                        ), the best results were observed for BRINE 5. The C-Dots dissolved in the brine at 5000 mg.L-1 delayed the cell proliferation, thus keeping the count under 5 log CFU/g throughout the entire storage period. Delayed microbial growth in the active samples was also observed for the coliforms (Table 4
                        ). COAT and all the active samples kept the cell count below 5 log CFU/g for a maximum of 15 days, while the control cheese exceeded 6 log CFU/g after 10 days of storage. A gradual increase in lactic acid bacteria and Lactococcus was observed in all the samples over the two-week monitoring period (data not shown). Therefore, no actual inhibition of the proliferation of useful bacteria was triggered in the presence of C-Dots, even though the growth of these microbial groups in both samples with C-Dots in the brine was found to slow down compared to the other samples. To sum up, the increased availability of C-Dots particles in the brine has fostered greater antimicrobial efficacy on the spoilage groups, compared to C-Dots loading in the coating; therefore, samples with C-Dots in brine were more interesting.
